IREX 10: Identification Track

IREX 10 Homepage | API | FAQ | CONOPS Document | irex@nist.gov

Introduction

The IREX 10: Identification Track assesses iris recognition performance for identification (a.k.a one-to-many) applications.  Most flagship deployments of iris recognition operate in identification mode, providing services ranging from prison management, border security, expedited processing, and distribution of resources.  Administered at the Image Group’s Biometrics Research Lab (BRL), developers submit their matching software for testing over sequestered iris data.  As an ongoing evaluation, developers may submit at any time.

Leaderboard

Accuracy Metric : FNIR (i.e., “miss rate”) at an FPIR of 0.01(± 90% confidence)
Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500K people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

The number after the ± indicates either the 90% confidence interval (for accuracy) or the standard deviation (for times).

Detection-Error Trade-off Plots

Core accuracy for the identification task can be characterized by Detection-error trade-off (DET) plots. Generally, curves lower down in a DET plot correspond to more accurate matchers. The plots are interactive through the use of the Plotly.js graphing library.

Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500K people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person
Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: One eye
Enrolled Population: 1M irides
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Rank Accuracy

Rank-based metrics quantify accuracy for closed-set applications, where it can be guaranteed that every searched individual is enrolled. The rank 10 “hit rate” is the fraction of searches that return the correct candidate within the top 10 candidates. The miss rate is one minus the hit rate.

Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500K people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Computation Time

Computation times are measured as the the elapsed real time (i.e., “wall clock” time) as opposed to CPU time. Timing estimates were computed on unloaded machines with only a single process dedicated to biometric operations. The test machines are Dell PowerEdge M910 blades with Dual Intel Xeon X7560 2.3 GHz CPUs (with eight cores per processor).

Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500K people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Some consolidation of demographic information was necessary to improve statistical power. Eye colour was consolidated to either light (grey, blue, or green) or dark (brown or black). Some subjects were labeled as being neither male nor female. Meaningful results for these categories could not be obtained because their sample sizes are too small. For the same reason, results for races other than white and black are not shown. The precise definitions of race, sex, and eye colour used here can be EBTS version 10.0.

Logistic Regression

This section models the relationship between FNIR and various demographic characteristics using logistic regression. The response variable is whether the search produces a false negative at an FPIR of \(0.01\). The precise logit relationship is

ℓ = log p 1-p = β0 + β1 Sex + β2 Race + β3 Eye color + β4 Sex and Eye Colour + β5 Sex and Race

where p is the probability of a false negative and ℓ is the log likelihood ratio of the probability of a false negative.

The model does not include any interactions between race and eye colour because the were not enough cases of blacks with light eyes to produce meaningful results. Eye colour was unavailable for some subjects so MICE was used to perform imputation.
Estimate Standard Error p
(Intercept) -5.25 0.03 < 0.001
Female 0.74 0.07 < 0.001
Black -0.11 0.07 0.149
Light Eyes -0.42 0.09 < 0.001
Female, Black 0.39 0.13 0.005
Female, Light Eyes -0.11 0.17 0.296

n = 335,202
Tjur’s R2 = 0.00017

Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500K people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Negative (blue) values mean the probability of a miss is decreased. Tjur’s R2 metric is a measure of the goodness-of-fit that produces values between 0 and 1. Precisely, it is the difference between the mean predicted probability for true positives (0.0013) minus the mean predicted probability for false negatives (0.0011). Race, sex, and eye colour are generally poor predictors of accuracy, so the value is typically low.

False Matches

This section investigates whether those with similar demographic characteristics are more likely to falsely match with one another. The figure below shows how often false matches occur between iris samples from persons having the same sex, race, and eye hue. The shading shows 90% confidence intervals, which tend to widen going right to left. as the number of false positives decreases. The confidence interval is wider for eye hue since eye colour was unavailable for the majority of subjects. The dotted lines represents expected behavior if false positives are uncorrelated with the demographic characteristic.

The test dataset is 79% male, 83% white (12% black), with 91% having dark eyes (i.e. brown or black).

Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500K people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Automated Quality Assessment

Participants were encouraged (but not required) to assign quality values to iris samples (as defined in ISO 19794-6). The participants who opted to do so are Idemia, Neurotechnology. The concept of an error-reject curve was first proposed in PAMI Vol 28 Issue 4. The authors proposed that an effective quality assessor should produce values that positively correlate with comparison accuracy. Discarding the poorest quality samples should therefore reduce identification failures.

The figure below demonstrates that the rank 1 miss rate can be reduced by roughly 20% by discarding just 1% of the poorest quality samples. Presumably, this 1% consists of samples where the subject was blinking, moving, looking off-axis at the moment of capture, etc. The IREX 4 failure analysis found that matching failures for a similar iris dataset are almost entirely due to poor presentation of the iris.

Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: One eye
Enrolled Population: 1M irides
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

How to Participate

Participation is open to any commercial or academic organization free of charge. The first step is to mail the signed Participation Agreement and Data Transfer Agreement to NIST. Instructions on building a submission can be found in the concept of operations (CONOPS) document. The CONOPS document is supplemented by the irex.h and structs.h. To assist with development, a minimal working “stub” (a.k.a null implementation) is also available. See also our FAQ.

Participants are allowed to submit an implementation once every 3 calendar months.

Please send comments and recommendations to irex@nist.gov.

Contact Info

Inquiries and comments may be submitted to irex@nist.gov. Subscribe to the IREX mailing list to stay up-to-date on all IREX-related activities.
